benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: DELETE /1.0/kb/admin/cache/tenants - Invalidates Caches per tenant level

covered: Valid Deletion: TC01 confirms successful 204 with empty body and cache invalidation
Non-Existent Resource: TC04 handles 404 for non-existent tenant context
Authorization: TC02 and TC03 cover missing and invalid authentication
Server Error Handling: TC05 covers 500 internal error
Service Unavailable: TC06 covers 503 service unavailable
Malformed Request: TC07 covers 400 for extra/unsupported parameters
Security - Injection: TC08 covers 400/403 for invalid input in headers
Edge Case - Empty Cache: TC09 covers 204 when cache already empty (idempotence)
Performance/Load: TC10 covers concurrent requests and performance criteria
Regression: TC11 ensures previously fixed issue remains fixed
Integration: TC12 ensures dependent services observe invalidation
State Variation: TC13 handles partially populated cache invalidation
Timeout: TC14 covers 504 when invalidation times out
Background/Setup: Tests ensure proper tenant context and authentication setup
gaps: Caching Behavior: No tests asserting HTTP caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control) or explicit caching semantics beyond invalidation
Explicit Pagination or Large Dataset Handling: Not applicable to this endpoint but guidelines mention; none present
Rate Limiting Explicit Assertions: TC10 implies load testing but no explicit throttling or retry semantics
Soft Deletes or Audit Trails: Not applicable for cache invalidation endpoint
recommendations: Add tests to validate HTTP caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control) and cache-control semantics for invalidation responses
Document and test explicit rate-limiting/throttling behavior and retries for rapid successive DELETEs
Consider a small set of tests for idempotence across repeated invalidations to ensure consistent behavior
Include any additional integration tests verifying that dependent services receive and reflect the invalidation signal in a traceable way
